<HEAD>Agreement Rejected, Rail Service Headed for Court</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> is on a fast track to criminal court
after refusing to stop flushing toilet waste from trains.
   State Attorney <PERSON>John Tanner</PERSON>, who filed littering charges against
the passenger railroad, had offered to drop the three misdemeanor
counts if <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> agreed to stop dumping from trains passing over two
overwater trestles.
   But <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION>, whichhas been dumping along its right of way under a
federal law that railroads have been using for more than a century,
contends federal law overrides state and local law. <PERSON>Clifford Black</PERSON>,
an <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> spokesman at its <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> headquarters, said <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>
risks losing service if it presses the case.
   An arraignment was scheduled <DATE>Sept. 18</DATE>. The charges carry fines of
up to <MONEY>$5,000</MONEY> each.
   <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION>'s 600 passenger cars dispose of sewage either by dumping
directly onto the tracks when toilets are flushed or by spraying the
contents of 30-gallon holding tanks when the trains are traveling at
least 35 mph.
   Tanner tried to halt the practice only over the two trestles.
   Black said agreeing to <PERSON>Tanner</PERSON>'s conditions would make <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> a
target for similar demands over every body of water in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>.
``With the myriad waterways in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>, it would be an impossible
situation,'' he said <DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   The railroad hopes to replace much of its fleet with new cars
equipped with holding tanks for all toilets. Black said it would
cost <MONEY>$147 million</MONEY> to install those tanks on the current fleet.
   Amtrak fears having to hire a worker to stand in each car to
throw an override switch for toilets when the trains cross bodies of
water, <ORGANIZATION>Black</ORGANIZATION> said.
   <PERSON>Tanner</PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> is bluffing and could not afford to cut back
service in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> or the Western states _ <LOCATION>Oregon</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Utah</LOCATION>,
<LOCATION>California</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Nevada</LOCATION> _ where it has also come under fire for its
sanitary habits.
   Black said that the criminal case is the only one of its kind
against <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> of which he is aware. Two civil cases are pending in
<LOCATION>Oregon</LOCATION>, he said.
</TEXT>
