<HEAD>Amtrak Pleads Innocent in Sewage-Dumping Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALATKA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amtrak pleaded innocent <DATE>Monday</DATE>, via
facsimile machine, to charges that it illegally flushes
passenger-car toilets and sewage tanks when its trains cross <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>
waterways, where fishermen have been sprayed.
   The transmission of the pleas to Circuit <PERSON>Judge Robert Perry</PERSON>
quickly ended an arraignment, said <ORGANIZATION>Assistant State</ORGANIZATION> Attorney <PERSON>Paul
Meredith</PERSON>. The judge scheduled a <DATE>Nov. 2</DATE> hearing for pre-trial motions.
   <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> has threatened to halt service in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>.
   The plea was entered after <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> earlier rejected a settlement
offer from State Attorney <PERSON>John Tanner</PERSON>, who promised to drop three
charges of commercial dumping if <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> would stop all flushing
while its trains cross trestles over creeks and rivers in his
judicial district.
   <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION>, which has been dumping along its tracks under a federal
law dating back more than a century, said it can't do that because
it would set a precedent.
   The federal law permits the railway to flush toilets along its
right-of-way, and federal law overrides state and local regulations,
<ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> contends.
   <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> has also come under fire in several Western states for its
sanitary habits, but <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Clifford Black</PERSON> said this is
the first complaint filed in a criminal court.
   <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> had threatened to suspend service in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION> if <PERSON>Tanner</PERSON>
pressed his case, but <PERSON>Tanner</PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> was bluffing.
   ``We hope we won't have to suspend service to <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>,'' said
<ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON>Sue Martin</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>D.C.</LOCATION> ``But we are
between a rock and a hard place and we certainly do not want to
continue this public embarrassment. We do not want to be accused of
committing a felony every day.''
   Tanner filed the misdemeanor counts after getting complaints from
people who said they were sprayed with raw sewage while fishing
beneath trestles in the <LOCATION>Palatka</LOCATION> area of northeastern <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Tanner</PERSON>
said the charges would be dropped if <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION> agreed to stop dumping
over <LOCATION>Rice Creek</LOCATION>, a tributary of the <LOCATION>St. Johns River</LOCATION>, and in the
river itself.
   Black said agreeing to <PERSON>Tanner</PERSON>'s conditions would have made <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION>
a target for similar demands from anyone else wanting to stop
dumping in any body of water in <LOCATION>Florida</LOCATION>.
   <ORGANIZATION>Amtrak</ORGANIZATION>'s passenger cars dispose of sewage either by dumping
directly onto the tracks when toilets are flushed or by spraying the
contents of 30-gallon holding tanks along the tracks when the trains
are traveling at least 35 mph.
   The company hopes eventually to replace much of its fleet with
cars that would have holding tanks for all toilets. Black said it
would cost <MONEY>$147 million</MONEY> to install those tanks on the current fleet.
</TEXT>
