to clean the resin beads at water plants, so people don't have to use their
home water allotments to flush the purifiers.;    <PERSON>Johnson</PERSON> said her company
installs water flow restricters such as low-flow shower heads to make up for
the water used to clean the systems that it sells.;    "We dread having people
shut everything off because they are wasting water," said <PERSON>Pam Workman</PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION>Rayne
Water Conditioning Systems</ORGANIZATION>, which has 14,000 customers in the <LOCATION>San Jose</LOCATION> area.
"There are alternatives.";    In response to the drought, <PERSON>Rayne</PERSON> has developed
a water softener that uses only 12 gallons per regeneration flush. But few
other companies have followed suit.;    The <ORGANIZATION>Santa Clara Valley Water District</ORGANIZATION>
advises people with water softeners to shut them off for the duration of the
drought. If they can't stomach the water, the district is requesting that
people try to reduce the timing of their softener flushing cycles to once a
week or less.;     How much do they flush?; Here is about how much water
selected automatic softening systems use each time they clean the resin
filters after 1,000 gallons of water have been purified. The frequency of
flushing varies with household water use but is generally every one to three
days.; Type of softener         Minutes water runs    Avg. gallons; ...;
Servisoft Comput-a-Save 1230             45              35; <ORGANIZATION>Culligan Mark</ORGANIZATION> 59
Aqua Sensor            140              45; <ORGANIZATION>Sears</ORGANIZATION> Kenmore Cycle Miser 34280N  
      90              50; <PERSON>Marlo MP255</PERSON>                             100         
    50; Rayne RT2000                            115             120; Source:
<ORGANIZATION>Santa Clara Valley Water District</ORGANIZATION>; Consumer Reports; <ORGANIZATION>Mercury News</ORGANIZATION>; ...; The
process; This is how a water softener works:; (box) Mineral-rich "hard" water
flows through a tank filled with resin beads, which remove the minerals and
other particles.; (box) The particle-free "soft" water flows directly to
outlets in the home or business.; (box) As the resin beads remove the
minerals, they slowly get saturated with "hard" material. They must be cleaned
every few days so they can continue to grip onto particles. This is done by
running saltwater through the resin.; (box) After the saltwater cleanses the
beads, it runs down the drain.  </TEXT>
